      "bodyEn": [
        "In 1997, I worked at a private clinic in Liantang, Shenzhen for a period of time. On the day I applied, an elderly doctor around 70 was drying Chinese herbs out front. I approached and asked, \"Excuse me, sir, are you still hiring TCM doctors?\" The old gentleman looked at me — a man in my early thirties — and replied with great delight, \"Yes, yes! Just a few days ago I told the boss we need a young fellow to assist me! Come with me, I'll take you to the boss!\"",
        "Back in those days, most people were lucky to have a pager. Phone calls were made at public payphones. Yet on the old doctor's desk stood a \"brick phone\" (early mobile phone) — it looked extremely impressive! I later learned he claimed to be a retired expert from a major hospital in inland China. Inside the large consultation room, five doctors sat in a row from front to back; three others were Western medicine practitioners. The old doctor sat first in line, and I sat last. Naturally, he was the clinic's mainstay — every patient went to him first, and only those he couldn't get to were passed to the doctors behind. The clinic had no shortage of patients. On my very first day, a patient was already referred to me. I remember my first patient was a woman in her twenties, brought in by her boyfriend. She had abdominal pain and walked in slowly, bent over. She told me the clinic had been treating her with both Chinese and Western medicine for three days, but the pain hadn't lessened. Western medicine was administered first via IV drip — in those days, clinics would throw both Western medicine and TCM at every patient so the boss could make more money. Even though I sat at the back, the boss directly assigned me to do pulse diagnosis and combine it with herbal treatment. I figured he wanted to test my skills. I examined her: tongue was yellow, thick, and greasy. I asked about her bowel movements in recent days. Answer: none. Her lower abdomen was tender to pressure with rebound pain at the McBurney's point — clearly appendicitis. Fortunately the inflammation was being controlled by the IV antibiotics. Right then and there, I prescribed a modified Cheng Qi Tang (Order the Qi Decoction). I remember using 30 grams of Da Huang (rhubarb root). When the boss saw the prescription, he pulled me aside and asked, \"30 grams of Da Huang?! Are you sure this is safe?!\" I said, \"Don't worry. Give her one dose, and she'll bring you good news tomorrow.\"",
        "Sure enough, early the next morning, the woman arrived with her boyfriend, beaming. She said that after going home, decocting the herbs, and taking them, she passed a large amount of dark, foul-smelling stool, and the illness seemed to vanish instantly! The boss was overjoyed!!! At the same time, you could see the wheels turning in his head as he schemed!!! Over the next few days, the boss began steering patients my way, deliberately or not. After a month, the boss found an excuse to let the old doctor go!!! He later said to me, \"What a fraud!!! Claimed to be an expert — in all these months he hasn't properly cured a single patient!!!\""
      ]
