        "July 28, 2013 – Fourth visit: Had some coughing on Wednesday and Thursday this week around 3–4 AM. Last night before bed, productive cough with phlegm expectorated (previously always dry cough). No coughing during the daytime. The child's father remarked that such a good state of health has been rare in recent years; previously, coughing and wheezing would flare up every couple of days. Mild nasal allergic reaction upon waking (nasal itching, runny nose, sneezing). Some redness and itching still around the eyelids.",
        "The child's father asked: 'We've seen many TCM practitioners before and taken plenty of herbal medicine — why was there never a good result?' I answered: 'For most cough and asthma disorders, spleen-kidney deficiency, spleen-lung deficiency, or lung-kidney deficiency are common — these all fall under yang deficiency or qi deficiency. Treatment typically focuses on tonifying and regulating spleen-lung yang qi or lung-kidney yang qi. The theoretical basis is that the spleen is the source of phlegm production while the lung is the vessel that stores phlegm. Hence practitioners focus on the spleen and kidney, aiming to cut off the root of cough and asthma, using warming, tonifying, and phlegm-resolving methods. However, your child's cough and asthma is characterized by scanty phlegm, absence of phlegm, or dry cough, accompanied by allergic symptoms such as dry, itching skin and eyes. This clearly is not a spleen-lung problem, nor a spleen-kidney yang deficiency problem. Rather, it is a liver-lung problem — \"wood fire torturing metal.\" At the initial visit there were exterior manifestations with concurrent liver-lung interior heat. From the second visit onward the exterior patterns had resolved, after which treatment focused on the root — clearing the liver and nourishing the lung.'",
