      "images": [
        "img/case_18_1.png"
      ],
      "bodyEn": [
        "In the 1990s, a friend's child — at the time about 3 or maybe 5 years old, I can't quite recall — was living in a small town in Hubei province. This was early autumn. Hubei is a region of heavy damp-heat.",
        "At the time, the child had a daily fever. Was hospitalized at the local township hospital for a week, received IV fluids each day — the fever would subside after the infusion, only to return the next day, followed by another infusion to bring the fever down again. This cycle repeated daily. Blood tests showed nothing abnormal. The following week, the child was transferred to a regional major hospital — yet the outcome was the same as the first week: IV fluids brought the fever down, then fever returned, then more IV fluids, repeating for another entire week. The hospital suspected typhoid or paratyphoid fever but could not confirm through lab markers.",
        "In desperation, they consulted me over the phone. I asked about the child's tongue presentation — whether the coating was thick or thin. Answer: thick! I asked: yellow or white? Answer: white!",
        "Taking into account the season and the geographical region, I diagnosed it as damp-warm disease (seasonal damp-heat febrile disorder). I prescribed a formula over the phone, mainly to disinhibit dampness and clear heat. I told them to give one dose first and call back the next day with an update.",
        "The following day, they called to say that the fever subsided right after taking the medicine, and the next day there was no recurrence of fever as had been the pattern before. They asked whether to switch formulas. I replied: continue with the original prescription for 2 more doses. I advised them to discharge the child and stop the Western medical treatment.",
        "Result: From the very first dose onward, the fever never returned, and no further Western medicine was used. Afterwards, I gave a slight follow-up adjustment formula to complete the treatment."
      ]
