      "hasReports": false,
      "body": [
        "各种药在用量大小不一，其作用也是有差异，医生用药的意向也是根据病情取向。比如，麻黄，用量小有宣肺之功，用量大有发汗之作用。",
        "石膏，用量小有解肌宣透作用，用量大有沉降泻火作用。",
        "遇辩证有“肺郁化燥”，所以用石膏等。",
        "一个处方有个总方向，同时可以根据病情的复杂程度还可配以其他的升降浮沉方向。",
        "一个病人得病，不可能比着一个成方或经方来患病，往往因个人的体质不一样，先天素质的差异、以及各种兼证不一等，在处理治疗过程中就得看医生是否能全面掌握病情，并能分清主次轻重，组方配药丝丝入扣。",
        "同样一个处方，任何调改一下方中任何一味药的份量，其方最终的治疗方向（归经、主治、兼治、表里、寒热、升降、浮沉、汗下吐和清温消补八法等）可能完全不一样的。所以，仅凭一个处方的药名来判断该方的具体走向，必然是不能具体到位的。因此，没有必须在论坛中纠结这些。",
        "我不想在论坛中纸上谈兵，也不想在论坛中与任何人争论什么。这类技术问题，根本不是在论坛中通过讨论能得到提高的。",
        "古人对学医人早有总结：学医三年，无不治之病；治病三年，无治病之方；再过三年，方可见悟！",
        "现代学医人也一样逃不出古人的经验总结，大家各自努力学习、多实践才是真正的出路！",
        "理论学习、与实践结合才是中医的生存之道。现代中医的失败就在于理论与实践的脱离。夸夸其谈者，不一定能治病！",
        "前些天到北京某中医院与一中医主任朋友（他本人是中西医结合专业出生，现为专家级）聊天，聊到他对中西医的认识时，他说了一句：“真治病还得靠西医，中医只能治不是病的病！”此话一出，让我这学中医的人心里顿感酸楚，心中感慨：中医在中国可能真的要完了！国家培育出的中医就是这样认识中医的！他们是主医的主流，是具表现性的！",
        "我一个小小人物，面对现状，还能说什么呢？在论坛上、在中医群中，还有什么可值得争论的呢？何况中医几千年，各家学说、各派理论众多，谁又能说得清哪家的就是最正确的？自己的中医理论没有错？别人的就是错的？真没有必要争论或辩论！",
        "唯一让我下定决心的是：自己要好好学习、努力学习各家学说，坚持实践，不断提高自己！自己坚持用中医药为病人能治好病，是我唯一的心愿！",
        "我只想在中医这块自留地中默默地耕耘！不想与任何人在论坛或群中辩论什么！所以也希望大家能谅解，以后我不会在论坛中或群中回答他人提出的与中医相关的质疑内容！"
      ],
      "bodyEn": [
        "Various herbs differ in dosage, and their effects also differ. The doctor's intention in prescribing is based on the orientation of the disease pattern. For example, Ephedra (Ma Huang) in small doses has the function of dispersing the lung, while in large doses it has the effect of inducing sweating.",
        "Gypsum (Shi Gao) in small doses has the action of releasing the muscle layer and diffusing outward, while in large doses it has a settling and fire-draining effect.",
        "When the pattern differentiation reveals 'lung depression transforming into dryness,' gypsum and similar herbs are thus used.",
        "A prescription has an overall direction, and depending on the complexity of the condition, other ascending, descending, floating, and sinking directions may also be incorporated.",
        "When a person falls ill, it is impossible for their condition to match exactly a ready-made or classical formula. Often, due to individual constitutional differences, innate variations, and various concurrent symptoms, the treatment process depends on whether the doctor can fully grasp the condition, distinguish primary from secondary and severe from mild, and formulate the prescription with meticulous precision.",
        "For the same prescription, adjusting the dosage of any single herb can result in a completely different final therapeutic direction (channel entry, primary indication, concurrent treatment, exterior/interior, cold/heat, ascending/descending, floating/sinking, the eight methods of sweating, vomiting, purging, harmonizing, warming, clearing, dispersing, and tonifying, etc.). Therefore, judging a prescription's specific direction based solely on herb names inevitably fails to be precise. Hence, there is no need to dwell on these matters in forums.",
        "I do not wish to engage in armchair theorizing in forums, nor do I want to argue with anyone in forums. Such technical issues are simply not something that can be improved through forum discussions.",
        "The ancients long ago summarized the path of medical study: after three years of studying medicine, there is no disease one cannot treat; after three years of treating diseases, there is no formula that reliably works; after another three years, one finally begins to see enlightenment!",
        "Modern medical students likewise cannot escape this ancient empirical observation. Diligent study by all and abundant practice is the true way forward!",
        "The integration of theoretical study with clinical practice is the path to survival for Chinese medicine. The failure of modern TCM lies in the disconnection between theory and practice. Those who speak eloquently may not necessarily be able to cure diseases!",
        "A few days ago, at a certain TCM hospital in Beijing, while chatting with a TCM director friend (who has an integrated Chinese-Western medicine background and is now an expert-level specialist), when the conversation turned to his understanding of Chinese and Western medicine, he said: 'When it comes to truly treating diseases, one still must rely on Western medicine; Chinese medicine can only treat ailments that aren't really diseases!' These words instantly left me, a TCM practitioner, feeling deeply bitter. My heart lamented: Chinese medicine in China may truly be finished! This is how TCM doctors cultivated by the state understand TCM! They are the mainstream doctors, the representative face of the profession!",
        "As a mere nobody, facing the current situation, what more can I say? In forums, in TCM groups, what is there still worth debating? Moreover, Chinese medicine spans thousands of years, with numerous schools of thought and various theoretical traditions — who can truly say which school is most correct? That one's own TCM theory is without error? That others' are wrong? There is truly no need for argument or debate!",
        "The only thing I am determined to do is: study diligently myself, work hard to learn from all schools of thought, persist in clinical practice, and constantly improve myself! Persisting in using Chinese medicine to cure patients is my sole aspiration!",
        "I only wish to quietly cultivate this reserved plot of Chinese medicine! I do not want to debate anything with anyone in forums or groups! So I also hope everyone can understand — henceforth I will not answer TCM-related skeptical questions posed by others in forums or groups!"
      ]
