      "body": [
        "说两例我了解的例子：",
        "一例是一男子，40多岁，原来每年单位都给做全面体检，一切正常。突然遇车祸股骨骨折了，治疗前做了个全面体检，“意外发现”肝有一10公分大小的肿瘤，然后定为肝癌。医院自然会要求做一系列的放化疗，刚做完第一疗程（15天）时，经朋友介绍来看中医。当时面黄无血色、精神极度疲乏，用中药一周后，面色及精神明显好转，我建议其家人不要继续做放放疗，以后身体调理强后可以考虑手术。这时家人中有不同意见了：老婆认可中医保守治疗方案，姐姐强烈要求继续放化疗，中西医同步进行（出院休养期间配合中药增强体质能力）。同时姐姐丢出一句话：要是不按医院的方案进行，人没命了谁负责？！媳妇无语，只能继续第二轮放化疗，又一个15天出院后再次找我时，我一看脸色又打回原形了，而且比第一次来时更差了。我提醒说：再做放、化疗可能这人真要完蛋了，再次建议停止放化疗。姐姐再度坚持继续按原方案进行，在第三次进行到一半时，人体全身发黄，医院这时说：癌细胞扩散了，不宜再做了，要求病人立即出院（每当这时，医院再不说对生命有保障的话了）。家属这时电话联系我反应了情况，问还有希望吗？我说，没有办法了，这种状态我没这能力了，第一次时要是听我的建议可能不至于这样。最后没有过半月病人归天了。",
        "第二例：女性，医院查出子宫颈癌。经人介绍来找我，给开了一方，并告诉病人及家属说:服药后可能会放臭屁、排臭便，有这反应时不用担心，是排毒现象，也是有救的希望。如果吃了没有任何反应，那也真不好治，同时告诫这类病尽量不要做放化疗。虽然反复给病人及其家属说清了服药后的表现及利害关系，可病人在服药i 不到一周还是主动放弃了中药，原因是这样：1、吃药后每天放臭屁，奇臭无比，病人老公后来说太臭，病人自己说臭得受不了（真不明白病人为什么会受不了，前面作了详细解释）。2、医院给病人及家属洗脑：\"这类病要按国际贯例进行治疗，不要吃中药，否则生命就无保证了”（恐吓病人）。在病人及其母亲的强烈要求下，放弃中药，按国际贯例进行了，第一轮花了3万多。同一病房的另一相同病的病人，在同一时间段花的钱近100万，原因是：医生先了解病人及家人的经济收入能力，然后“量身定制”，总有一款适合每一位病人。这些是病人老公后来含着泪水告诉我的，我听后无语，只能在心中为他祈福。"
      ],
      "images": [
        "img/case_24_1.jpeg"
      ],
      "bodyEn": [
        "Let me share two examples I am familiar with:",
        "The first case: A man in his 40s. Previously, his workplace provided annual comprehensive physical examinations, and all results were normal. He was suddenly involved in a car accident and sustained a femoral fracture. A full physical exam was done before treatment, and it \"unexpectedly discovered\" a 10 cm tumor in the liver, which was then diagnosed as liver cancer. The hospital naturally recommended a series of radiotherapy and chemotherapy. Just after completing the first course (15 days), a friend referred him to see a TCM practitioner. At that time his face was sallow and bloodless, and his energy was extremely depleted. After one week of Chinese herbal medicine, his complexion and energy visibly improved. I advised his family not to continue radiotherapy and chemotherapy, and suggested that once his body was stronger, surgery could be considered. At this point the family had differing opinions: the wife was in favor of the TCM conservative treatment plan, while the elder sister strongly demanded continuing radiotherapy and chemotherapy, with both Western and Chinese medicine running in parallel (using Chinese herbs to strengthen the body during discharge rest periods). The sister dropped a line: \"If we don't follow the hospital's protocol and the person dies, who will take responsibility?!\" The wife was silenced, and they could only proceed with the second round of radiotherapy and chemotherapy. After another 15 days, when discharged and visiting me again, I saw that his complexion had regressed to its original state — and was even worse than the first visit. I warned that continuing radiotherapy and chemotherapy would likely kill this person, and again recommended stopping. The elder sister once more insisted on continuing the original plan. Halfway through the third round, the patient's entire body turned yellow. The hospital then said: the cancer cells have spread; further treatment is not advisable — the patient must be discharged immediately. (At times like this the hospital never again speaks of guaranteeing the patient's life.) The family contacted me by phone describing the situation and asked: Is there still hope? I said: There's nothing I can do. In this state, I don't have the ability. If you had listened to my advice the first time, things might not have come to this. In the end, less than half a month later, the patient passed away.",
        "The second case: A woman was diagnosed with cervical cancer at the hospital. Someone referred her to me, and I wrote a prescription, telling the patient and her family: After taking the medicine, she may pass foul-smelling gas and foul-smelling stools. If this reaction occurs, do not worry — it is a detoxification phenomenon, and it also means there is hope of recovery. If there is no reaction at all after taking the medicine, then it truly is difficult to treat. At the same time I cautioned that, for this kind of illness, radiotherapy and chemotherapy should be avoided as much as possible. Although I repeatedly explained the expected reactions and the pros and cons to the patient and family, the patient voluntarily gave up Chinese herbal medicine in less than a week. The reasons were as follows: 1. After taking the medicine, she passed foul-smelling gas every day — extraordinarily foul. The husband later said it was too foul, and the patient herself said she could not stand the smell. (I truly cannot understand why the patient could not endure it, given the detailed explanation provided beforehand.) 2. The hospital brainwashed the patient and family: \"This type of illness must be treated according to international protocol. Do not take Chinese herbs, otherwise your life cannot be guaranteed.\" (Intimidating the patient.) Under strong insistence from the patient and her mother, Chinese herbs were abandoned and the international protocol was followed. The first round cost over 30,000 yuan. Another patient with the same condition in the same ward and same period spent nearly 1 million yuan. The reason: the doctors first assessed the patient's and family's economic capacity, then \"tailor-made\" a plan — there is always a package for every patient. The husband told me this later with tears in his eyes. I listened in silence, and could only pray for her in my heart."
      ]
