      "bodyEn": [
        "Mr",
        "FREDERLD, 52 years old, French (husband of QL from the earlier gynecology case)",
        "First visit on 2012.8.26. The patient initially stated: he was in very good health with no uncomfortable sensations whatsoever; he simply wanted to resolve his high cholesterol (3.57 g/L).",
        "Upon taking his pulse, I found it was wiry and moderate but with a 'knotted-intermittent' (Jie Dai) quality (at that time, there was basically one missed beat every 4-5 heartbeats, and sometimes after 2-3 heartbeats). I asked, how does your heart feel? Do you have chest tightness or a sensation of cardiac blockage? At this, prompted by my question, he suddenly recalled and said that his heart often had a spasmodic sensation, with pain occurring in the cardiac region and various positions in the chest — very frightening! He was worried that what his GP had said about high LDL cholesterol leading to heart disease might be happening!",
        "Because I inferred from his wiry pulse that there was a liver problem, I asked further: have you had liver function tests at the hospital? Any issues? Only then did he say: he had contracted 'hepatitis B' at the age of 13, and currently his hepatitis B markers were normal, but he had extremely high cholesterol and an enlarged spleen. He had been an athlete in his youth and had always been very robust; his heart rate was somewhat slow. From outward appearance, his complexion and physique were very good.",
        "Looking at the tongue: slightly dark body, thin yellow and dry coating in the middle portion. I further inquired about his diet and whether he had any gastric discomfort. He replied: he frequently had a burning sensation in the stomach and acid reflux. I then asked: any discomfort in the hands and feet? He immediately remembered and said: when sitting with legs crossed or resting on his elbows for a while, his toes and fingers would go numb. I also asked about sleep. He said: not good; he would invariably wake naturally around 3 AM every day. I noted: 3 AM is the transition between the Chou and Yin hours, precisely when the liver and lung qi dynamic intersect, also indicating disharmony in the liver-lung qi dynamic.",
        "Final pattern diagnosis: 1. Liver qi and blood constraint leading to impeded and blocked qi and blood in the heart and lung, with insufficiency of qi and blood, causing ischemia in the limbs and heart-chest. 2. Liver qi invading the stomach causing mild gastric disease.",
        "From the above patient feedback combined with pulse and tongue assessment, the problem was one of devitalized qi and blood in the liver, spleen, stomach, and heart vessels. Many patients, without 'inquiry-style questioning,' are unaware they even have pathological conditions. Only when targeted inquiry is performed do they realize how many problems they actually have.",
        "I told him not to worry; Chinese herbal regulation would show good results in the near term, and with several months of persistence, there should be excellent therapeutic outcomes.",
        "The few points I had asked about were all his most prominent problems, which also amazed the patient! He said, 'My GP has never understood my condition this way. I am completely convinced by you!' And he added: 'When my GP previously prescribed Western medicine for liver and cholesterol issues, I kept taking the Western drugs, but both the liver condition and cholesterol were not cured; instead, I developed stomach problems from the medication. Now heart problems have also appeared. The problems are becoming more and more complex, and Western medicine has not been able to solve my problems. I am now uneasy about Western medicine.'",
        "I said, let's start with one week of herbs. He said: 'I would like to start with two weeks. I have confidence that the herbs you prescribe will definitely be excellent. My wife said her results were very good.' I replied: 'Alright, then start with two weeks, and come back for a follow-up after finishing.'",
        "Chinese herbal prescription: Chai Hu (Bupleurum), Xiang Fu (Cyperus)",
        "Mu Xiang (Aucklandia), Wu Yao (Lindera), San Qi (Notoginseng), Dan Shen (Salvia), Chuan Xiong (Ligusticum), Dang Gui (Angelica Sinensis), Huang Qi (Astragalus), Wa Leng Zi (Arc Shell), Fu Ling (Poria), Mai Ya (Malt Sprout), Sheng Ma (Cimicifuga), Gan Cao (Licorice)",
        "Decocted by the pharmacy; taken 3 times daily.",
        "2012/9/9",
        "Second visit: Upon taking his pulse, the knotted-intermittent pulse phenomenon was gone, and the pulse strength had increased. I knew the qi and blood had been invigorated, and the heart condition should be much improved. Upon inquiry, I learned: the cardiac spasmodic symptoms were markedly improved, with only occasional twitching, pain, and discomfort. He said his previous early-morning cough was also much better now. Moreover, the 3 AM waking phenomenon was also markedly reduced, and sleep quality had greatly improved. Numbness in hands and feet was also reduced. The gastric burning sensation was still present to some degree. Bowel movements had increased by one additional time per day.",
        "From multiple symptomatic perspectives, the results were very evident. The patient was very pleased and repeatedly said 'Thank you!!!' as he left. The patient requested to continue with another two weeks of herbs and then return for follow-up.",
        "And so, every two weeks he returned. Through continuous follow-ups and prescription adjustments, all the above heart, gastric, and other symptoms progressively reduced and disappeared with each visit. During the course of treatment, his work frequently required him to travel back and forth between China and France. During business trips, Chinese herbs had to be temporarily stopped, and there was travel fatigue. Consequently, there were occasional symptom recurrences and periods where progress temporarily plateaued. But overall, the direction was consistently positive.",
        "Initially, the herbs were decocted by the pharmacy. Later, I recommended he decoct them himself. After improving the decoction quality, the efficacy also greatly improved. By the follow-up on 2012.12.7, he reported that the cardiac pulse-intermittence phenomenon had 'not occurred even once' in the most recent two consecutive weeks (he checked himself daily). The results were very stable. This heart problem had been his greatest worry, and now he felt relieved. What made him even happier was that on January 18, 2013, he underwent tests in France, and compared with the pre-Chinese-herb test reports, his cholesterol had dropped from 3.57 g/L to 3.06 g/L, and all liver function markers had normalized. At the time, he was still continuing treatment, which should bring his cholesterol down to within the normal range (2.00 g/L)."
      ]
