        "Name: WY, male, 37 years old, Black (Zimbabwean, currently working in Beijing).",
        "When making the appointment by phone the day before, he stated that he suffered from prostatitis.",
        "September 9, 2012, Initial visit: Tongue coating thick, greasy, yellow, and dry with scant fluids. Pulse very weak and forceless (indicating significant deficiency). When taking his pulse I noticed his hands felt very cold, which in Chinese medicine is regarded as insufficiency of yang qi and kidney deficiency. All fingernail lunulae (health crescents) were absent, also indicating poor health and insufficient yang-type energy. (Through an interpreter) He reported long-term lower back pain over many years, recently occurring once every 20 minutes daily, with pain radiating to the lower abdomen, groin, and buttocks, plus knee joint pain and wrist joint pain. Long-term deep-yellow urine. Frequently prone to tonsillitis; marked dry throat upon waking in the morning. Small appetite, no desire to eat, easily bloated after meals. Poor sleep, also frequent heart-area pain and headaches. Weak sexual function; after intercourse the above pain symptoms would worsen. No pain on urination, but frequent urination. Bowel movement once daily, formed. Fatigue and lethargy all day long.",
        "I had not expected this to be a patient suffering from nearly systemic, long-term pain torment. Although the symptoms were very complex, with sufficient clinical experience it is easy to categorize and summarize them, find the root of the disease, and then treat according to the pattern to resolve the problem.",
        "Diagnosis: Liver and kidney deficiency and damage, spleen-kidney damp-heat accumulation, dampness having transformed into dryness.",
        "Treatment principle: Clear damp-heat, nourish liver and kidney yin, tonify deficiencies of liver, spleen, and kidney, invigorate blood and relieve pain.",
        "Prescription: Yi Ren (Coix Seed), Mu Xiang (Aucklandia), Zhi Qiao (Aurantium), Sheng Di (Rehmannia), Dan Shen (Salvia), Chai Hu (Bupleurum), Sheng Mu Li (Raw Oyster Shell), Huai Niu Xi (Achyranthes), Du Zhong (Eucommia), Chi Shao (Red Peony), Huang Qi (Astragalus), Dang Shen (Codonopsis), Sha Ren (Amomum), Ji Shi Teng (Paederia), Gan Cao (Licorice)",
        "Because the patient mentioned his financial situation was not good, I suggested that he must decoct the herbs himself — herbs decocted by hand at home produce a much more concentrated decoction than machine-decocted herbs from a pharmacy, so the effect is naturally much better, and it also saves money and shortens the treatment duration. One week, 7 doses, self-decocted, taken 3 times daily (this is the optimal method for Chinese herbal treatment).",
        "September 16, 2012, Second visit: Tongue coating thickness and greasiness markedly reduced compared to the previous visit (this change also surprised the interpreter, who carefully observed the patient across both consultations). Pulse deep and weak. The frequency of lower back and other pains had shifted from once every 20 minutes to once every 1.5–2 hours, and the pain intensity in the lower back, lower abdomen, and groin was noticeably reduced. Frequent urination decreased. Appetite improved, with a sense of hunger returning and food intake increased; no more bloating after meals. Sleep quality also showed marked improvement. Heart-area pain reduced from multiple episodes daily to once every other day. Headaches still present. After taking the medicine, frequent foul-smelling flatulence (a common phenomenon when taking Chinese herbs, indicating the body's functions are beginning to strengthen and it is expelling accumulated waste and toxins). Still experiencing fatigue and lethargy from 10 AM to 4 PM daily. Dry throat still present.",
        "The treatment effect was very good. He was advised to persist with treatment; the patient was also very happy, as this course of Chinese herbs gave him hope. At several subsequent follow-up visits, all aspects of the pain had markedly improved.",
