      "bodyEn": [
        "Wang XX, female, 26 years old, Occupation: Accountant.   2013.7.12 First Visit:",
        "Self-reported: Last year, when the company established a branch office, the workload was enormous. She worked frantically to meet deadlines, day and night, often with breakfast placed on the office desk, only to discover upon leaving work at 8 or 9 p.m. that breakfast still hadn't been eaten. After enduring this for several months, one day she suddenly had an accident in front of the elevator: her vision went dark, she lost consciousness, and she fell straight backward while standing... A large bump developed on the back of her head. Since then, she has frequently had dizziness and headaches. History of kidney stones.",
        "Currently: Dizziness, headache. Dark eye sockets, red eyes. Sallow, lusterless complexion. Facial butterfly-pattern pigmentation (melasma). Facial acne. Poor sleep quality, shallow sleep, dream-disturbed sleep. Difficulty getting up in the morning, daytime low energy. Lumbar pain, cold hands and feet, aversion to air-conditioning cold wind; exposure to cold triggers heel pain. Appetite average, bowel movements once every 1–2 days. Menstrual flow scant (cycle approximately 32 days, duration 3 days, color somewhat dark). Tongue: pale with thin yellow coating. Pulse: deep and weak (chen-ruo), guan position slightly slippery.",
        "Prescription: Dan Shen (Salvia), Shan Yu Rou (Cornus Flesh), Dang Gui (Angelica), Shan Yao (Dioscorea), Suan Zao Ren (Ziziphus Seed), Shou Wu (Polygonum), Huai Niu Xi (Achyranthes), Sha Ren (Amomum), Xiang Fu (Cyperus), Bai Shao (White Peony), Hou Po (Magnolia Bark), Gan Cao (Licorice). 7 doses.",
        "2013-7-19 Second Visit: Sleep quality improved. Lumbar pain resolved. Cold-aversion of hands and feet to air-conditioning cold wind improved. Appetite adequate. Bowel movements 2–3 times daily. Facial acne reduced. Dizziness and headache reduced. Pulse: slightly slippery. Tongue: pale with thin, scant coating.",
        "2013-7-26 Third Visit: Facial acne no longer appearing. Dizziness and headache no longer appearing. Sleep continued to improve; very little dreaming now. Morning difficulty getting up improved. Energy improved. Cold-aversion of hands and feet to air-conditioning cold wind continued to improve. Appetite adequate. Bowel movements multiple times daily. Also mentioned that since childhood she has been prone to colds and fever.",
        "2013-8-2 Fourth Visit: Occasional dizziness; headache no longer occurring. Eyes no longer red; dark eye sockets resolved. Face no longer breaking out in acne. Sleep good; no more difficulty getting up in the morning. Energy improved. Feet still fear air-conditioning.",
        "2013-8-9 Fifth Visit: Symptoms in all aspects basically resolved. Feet still slightly averse to air-conditioning cold wind. Pulse: harmonious and forceful.",
        "Advisory: Continue taking medication for a while longer to consolidate the therapeutic effect.",
        "This case exemplifies the consumptive disease typical of modern urbanites, with excessive depletion of bodily energy and excessive mental stress as the etiology. This physical body and its energy are finite; excessively depleting bodily energy is a very dangerous matter. From online reports in recent years, deaths from overwork (karoshi) have appeared from time to time, and this should attract everyone's sufficient attention.",
        "Among patients I have seen, one could say 70–80% share a similar etiology to this case. I hope everyone will promptly adjust their work and lifestyle intensity and rhythm, to ensure that the body can normally withstand the pressures of modern social development. Only when the body is safeguarded can an individual have sustainable developmental capacity; otherwise, one's current brilliance will only be transient.",
        "As much as possible in daily life, sleep early (before 11 p.m., ideally around 10:30), eat regularly in fixed amounts, and when off work, let go of all work-related rumination. Do more mental relaxation to reduce psychological stress. Go out with friends and colleagues more often to have fun and enjoy yourselves. Engage in appropriate physical exercise, and balance work with rest."
      ]
