        "Herpes pharyngitis is an acute infectious febrile disease caused by many group A Coxsackie viruses, and occasionally other enteroviruses. It is characterized by herpetic ulcerative mucosal lesions. Common in infants and young children.",
        "Clinical features: sudden high fever with sore throat, headache, anorexia, and often neck, abdominal, and limb pain. Infants frequently vomit and have convulsions. Within 2 days of onset, a small number (rarely more than 12) of small (1~2mm diameter) gray-white herpetic vesicles appear on the oral mucosa, surrounded by a red halo.",
        "They are commonly seen on the anterior tonsil but may also appear on the soft palate, tonsils, uvula, and tongue. Within the following 24 hours, the vesicles rupture into shallow ulcers. The ulcers are generally under 5mm in diameter and heal within 1~5 days.",
        "Complications are rare. Symptoms generally resolve within 7 days. Lasting immunity develops after infection, but other serotypes within group A or other enteroviruses may still cause recurrence.",
        "Zhou XX, male, 4 and a half years old, 2015.9.14. Mother narrates: Fever began yesterday afternoon. Hospital treatment was ineffective. Still has high fever today. Hospital diagnosis: herpes pharyngitis, and they do not rule out the possibility of hand-foot-and-mouth disease later. The mother originally came here for chronic bronchitis treatment herself and was very satisfied with the results. Today she came seeking medical help for her child.",
