        "Patient XX, female, 39 years old.",
        "Since middle school, she has had thyroid enlargement. Last year, thyroid nodules were discovered, and the hospital diagnosed Hashimoto's thyroiditis. This year, the nodules were found to have enlarged. Anti-thyroglobulin antibodies are elevated. She usually experiences irritability and depression (the thyroiditis has led to mental and emotional issues). During menstruation, she has oral ulcers, is prone to pharyngitis, dry throat, bad breath, and hot and sweaty palms and soles (indicating liver-stomach heat-toxin accumulation). An even more prominent symptom is a long-standing sensation of throat and neck distension and blockage (indicating severe local qi and blood stasis caused by the thyroid disease). She usually feels markedly fatigued, and every night before sleep, her legs feel sore and weak (indicating severe liver-kidney depletion). The tongue is red-crimson, dark and stagnant, with a yellow greasy coating (a typical tongue presentation of liver stasis and liver toxicity).",
