      "bodyEn": [
        "Ms. Yu XX, female, 31 years old. Initial consultation on March 28, 2011:",
        "She reported that in 2008, a Beijing hospital diagnosed her with Hashimoto's thyroiditis. Her tongue had teeth marks on the edges, and the anterior coating was thin and white while the root coating was thick and greasy. Her pulse was deep and weak. The thyroid gland was markedly enlarged, hard, and nodular. She felt a strong sense of constriction in the neck and often experienced difficulty breathing, which was especially noticeable when pushing her child on a bicycle at a brisk pace. She had a sensation of phlegm in the throat. Her lower back and legs were cold. She had palpitations and shortness of breath, tired easily, felt emotionally depressed, and was prone to irritability. Her appetite was somewhat excessive. Bowel movements occurred only once every several days. She had given birth to two children. (She had been on Western medication all along, with no significant effect.)",
        "Diagnosis: Kidney yang deficiency, liver qi stagnation, qi and blood deficiency.",
        "Prescription: Psoralea fruit, dodder seed, eucommia bark, curcuma root, bupleurum, chuanxiong, Chinese angelica, alisma, red peony, safflower, astragalus, prunella, etc. — 7 doses.",
        "Second visit on April 4, 2011: She reported that after taking just one dose of the above formula, the constriction in her neck eased and her breathing became much freer. She passed a lot of flatus. Bowel movements were still once every several days, but her drowsiness had diminished.",
        "Third visit on April 21, 2011: She felt the neck swelling was shrinking. The sensation of phlegm in the throat persisted. Her breathing improved further, and she now had a daily bowel movement.",
        "Fourth visit on May 12, 2011: The sensation of phlegm in her throat was gone. The day before, her child sustained a head injury, which caused major emotional upset; she felt the neck swelling increase again along with palpitations and shortness of breath.",
        "Fifth visit on May 19, 2011: The neck swelling had noticeably decreased, though she still felt it enlarge between 9 and 10 p.m. each evening. When pushing her child on a bicycle, she no longer experienced palpitations or shortness of breath. Her menses were dark in color and scanty in volume.",
        "Sixth visit on June 2, 2011: She occasionally still had a choking sensation in the neck. The swelling had almost returned to normal size; without close inspection, one could no longer tell that the thyroid was enlarged. The evening enlargement sensation (9–10 p.m.) had disappeared.",
        "Seventh visit on June 16, 2011: The thyroid was no longer enlarged. She was advised to continue taking the medicine for a while longer to consolidate the therapeutic effect.",
        "-------------------------------------------------------------------------",
        "Hashimoto's Thyroiditis (selected Western medical discussion follows):",
        "Thyroiditis is clinically classified into acute, chronic, suppurative, and non-suppurative types. Chronic lymphocytic thyroiditis, also known as Hashimoto's thyroiditis or autoimmune thyroiditis, has a fairly high incidence and is the most common cause of hypothyroidism in children. The incidence in school-age children can exceed 1%. The male-to-female ratio is 1:8. Onset is most frequent after age 6, with the peak age being 10–13 years.",
        "The pathogenesis of Hashimoto's thyroiditis is generally thought to involve both environmental factors and immune regulatory defects. It is classified as an organ-specific autoimmune disease. Evidence includes the detection of multiple autoantibodies in patient serum — primarily anti-thyroglobulin antibody (TGA) and anti-thyroid microsomal antibody (MCA). In a small number of patients, two additional types of antibodies — colloid antibody and cell surface antibody — can be detected by fluorescence immunoassay. T-cell and B-cell infiltration is seen in thyroid tissue. The disease has some genetic predisposition.",
        "Clinical symptoms of Hashimoto's thyroiditis: Onset is insidious, without distinctive sensations; patients often seek medical help because a goiter is discovered, or due to growth retardation or hypothyroid-like symptoms along with goiter. TGA and MCA are positive. In the early stage, the thyroid shows varying degrees of diffuse enlargement and soft texture. As the disease slowly progresses, the thyroid may become rubbery-hard with nodules of various sizes. The disease course spans several years. Symptoms may include nervousness, excessive sweating, and hyperactivity. Occasionally, due to thyroid follicle necrosis, thyroid hormones are released into the blood, causing a temporary rise in T3 or T4; in rare cases, it coexists with hyperthyroidism and exophthalmos may be present. A few patients, due to marked thyroid enlargement, may experience a sense of constriction in the neck. The disease progresses slowly; ultimately, due to thyroid atrophy, marked follicular epithelial changes, and fibrosis, hypothyroidism may develop several years later — in some cases becoming permanent. This disease can coexist with chronic adrenocortical insufficiency, diabetes, pernicious anemia, alopecia, and other conditions.",
        "Diagnosis of Hashimoto's thyroiditis: A typical clinical presentation with positive serum antibody tests establishes the diagnosis; however, even with positive antibodies, follow-up with repeat antibody testing is warranted. The following items can assist in diagnosis:",
        "1. Typical thyroid enlargement, which may be soft and smooth, or hard and nodular, without tenderness, without vascular bruits — absence of thyroid enlargement does not rule out the disease.",
        "2. Positive TGA and MCA (TGA > 30%, MCA > 20%). If both antibody tests are performed for each patient, the positivity rate can exceed 40%; however, a negative result does not exclude the disease.",
        "3. A family history of thyroid disease calls for extra caution; do not dismiss the diagnosis lightly.",
        "4. Refer to items 1 and 2 in the ancillary examinations to assist in diagnosis."
      ]
